Stroke Detection Analysis¶

Kush Vachher, Roderick Li

Introduction¶

Stroke is a critical issue within the United States. The Center for Disease Control and Prevention ranks it as the 5th leading cause of death with 165,393 deaths in 2022. To put this into perspective, someone in the US has a stroke every 40 seconds, and someone dies of stroke every 3 minutes and 14 seconds (CDC, 2024). These statistics highlight the urgent need for awareness and treatment of stroke. By analyzing this dataset, we may be able to find early indicators of stroke and more accurately predict those who are higher risk.

Along with its devastating effects on public health, stroke can also significantly strain the economy. According to the CDC, Stroke-related costs in the United States came to nearly $56.5 billion between 2018 and 2019(CDC, 2024). This enormous figure includes direct costs, such as medical expenses and rehabilitation, along with indirect costs like lost productivity and long-term disability care. Because stroke is a leading cause of disability in the United States, there is often a significant financial burden felt by families of victims as they seek out long-term care.

Given its significant impact on the United States health and economy, tackling stroke became a major concern for us as we explored potential topics for this project. Additionally, we have had friends and family affected by this disease, and we wanted to utilize the skills learned in this class to make a real-world impact.

In order to predict the onset of stroke, we will be going through the Data Science Lifecycle as following:

  1. Data Collection
  2. Data Processing
  3. Exploratory Analysis & Data Visualization
  4. Model: Analysis, Hypothesis Testing, & ML
  5. Interpretation: Insight & Policy Decision

Observe that the average BMI is highest for ages 50-60. It slowly rises from 10-50, with a large jump between 10-20 and 20-30. Oddly enough, average BMI goes down for age groups after 60. This is somewhat confusing - why would older patients tend to have lower BMI? According to ChenMed, certain diseases and treatments for disease can cause a weight loss among seniors. Some elders are also unable to afford nutrient-rich foods.

Step 4: Model: Analysis, Hypothesis Testing, & ML¶

In this phase, we will attempt to perform various modeling techniques (such as linear regression or logistic regression) on our set to obtain predictive data.

Our first model will be a logistic regression. First, we can temporarily drop columns that won't be used in the model.

In [148]:

Next, we must gather our features and target variable from the dataframe. This will be done by saving our predictor variables (non-stroke columns) as 'X' and our results (stroke column) as 'y'.

In [150]:
# Splitting the data into features (X) and target variable (y) using the modified copy
X = log_reg_df.drop('Stroke', axis=1)
y = log_reg_df['Stroke']

We will now use the Standard Scaler function from sklearn.preprocessing to remove the mean and scale X to unit variance. This simply generates z-scores for X, in place of the X value itself.

In [151]:
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)

The data will now be split into train and test sets. This is necessary to assess the performance of the regression model on unseen data and to prevent overfitting by evaluating its generalization ability.

In [152]:
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_scaled, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

We can final create the model using functions from sklearn.

In order to test our model's accuracy, we will utilize the test set created earlier and fit our model onto it. The accuracy metric will provide valuable insight into how well the model generalizes to new observations, and details how effective it can be moving forward.

In [154]:
# Predicting on the test set

Accuracy: 0.9393346379647749

Our model returned an accuracy of ~94%. Next, we will look at how each predicting variable impacted the prediction. This will be done by observing the coefficients within the regression.

In [155]:
coefficients = log_reg_model.coef_[0]
feature_names = X.columns

# Sort coefficients and feature names by coefficient value
sorted_indices = coefficients.argsort()
sorted_coefficients = coefficients[sorted_indices]
sorted_feature_names = feature_names[sorted_indices]

# Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.barh(sorted_feature_names, sorted_coefficients, color='skyblue')
plt.xlabel('Coefficient Value')
plt.ylabel('Feature')
plt.title('Coefficients of Features')

# Add coefficient values to the graph
for i, coef in enumerate(sorted_coefficients):
    plt.text(coef, i, f'{coef:.2f}', ha='right', va='center')

plt.show()

Observing this graph, we can see that age is overwhelmingly the most powerful predictor of an increased likelihood of stroke. As age increase, the log-odds of experiencing a stroke also increase. Some other positive coefficient predictors include Employment related to children, Average Glucose Level, Hypertension, Smoking, Heart Disease, and BMI. There are also a number of negative coefficient predictors, however none of them are of a large magnitude. Being self-employed results in a decrease in the log-odds of experiencing a stroke, but only by 0.16. Some other negative predictors include never having worked and working in a government job. There are also some confusing results - why does being previously being married decrease the likelihood of stroke?

Another thing to analyze is that our accuracy was relatively high, but we mentioned earlier that 95% of the data was stroke negative. This imbalance may give us the illusion that our model is doing better than it really is. Lets take a look at its accuracy, precision, and recall all together using classification report.

  1. More information about sklearn classficiation report can be found here: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.metrics.classification_report.html.
  2. Here is also a good video to watch to better understand the classification report: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XiUlqN1Ay0U&t=247s.

Inorder to handle the class imbalance, we are going to use SMOTE. SMOTE stands for Synthetic Minority Over-sampling Technique. Essentially, SMOTE will create synthetic data for the minority class. These synthetic instances are not present in the original dataset, but are created based on the characteristics of the minority class instances and their nearest neighbors.

More about smote can be found here in this free article: https://medium.com/@corymaklin/synthetic-minority-over-sampling-technique-smote-7d419696b88c

The link to smote documentation can be found here: https://imbalanced-learn.org/stable/references/generated/imblearn.over_sampling.SMOTE.html

Observe that our model actually made an effort to predict stroke here. This is a major improvement, even if it could only predict 70% of the true strokes correctly and has a high false positive rate. Before, our model was only predicting non stroke.

Although our accuracy dropped by 17%, our model is better as we are starting to somewhat accurately predict stroke. Our recall score is much higher compared to the original model, but our precision is somewhat low due to all the false positives.

In situations like this, it's crucial to prioritize minimizing false negatives over false positives. While false positives are generally acceptable, false negatives can have severe consequences. In this context, it's more preferable for someone who isn't experiencing a stroke to be overly cautious than for someone who is at risk to go undetected and potentially suffer adverse outcomes. Therefore, the focus should be on ensuring high sensitivity to accurately identify individuals at risk of stroke, even if it leads to an increase in false positives.

Step 5: Interpretation: Insight & Policy Decision¶

From our code, we are able to come to the conclusion that age plays the biggest factor in stroke. We are also able to conclude that BMI, hypertension, heartdisease, and average glucose level all have a positive correlation with stroke. All the other features, such as residency, previously married, and employment type, don't play as big as a role compared to the important features in predicting stroke.

We were able to create two models for logestic regression. One had an accuracy of ~94% and the other model had an accuracy of ~77%. While the first model may seem better, it had terrible precision and recall for the stroke class. The second model is much better even though it has low precision, but mediocre recall and accuracy. We have already concluded that is okay to have a high false positive rate as it is better to be overly cautious than carefree. A false positive rate in the senario of detecting stroke is much better than a false negative.

The only real way to improve the accuracy of the model would be to gather better data. More specifically, gather better data for stroke positive. It is hard for the model to pick up patterns in stroke if majority of the data is non stroke. It could be possible to gather stroke data from a different source and then intergrate it with the current dataset. Additionally, we could of also tried undersampling and doing a better job of tunning some hyper-parameters.

Moving forward, this data analysis could be used in medical devices to help predict stroke. The medical device would gather medical data, which would then be used to predict stroke. Being able to prevent the onset of stroke would be very beneficial to the United States as well as many other countries as stated in the introduction.
